<h1>@HI{{toki}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li>  @Vplain{{}}<strong>@HI{{toki}}</strong>
<li>  @Ai{{}}<strong>@HI{{toki}}</strong>
<li>  @Ana{{}}<strong>@HI{{toki}}</strong>
<li>  @N{{}}@HI{{no}}<strong>@HI{{toki}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{toki}}</strong> is a noun that indicates the time when something is or was done. It is often translated
as "at the time when".
</p>

<p>
@Vru{{}}<strong>@HI{{toki}}</strong> means that the action in the main clause happens <em>right before</em> that in the
relative clause.
</p>

<p>
@Vta{{}}<strong>@HI{{toki}}</strong> means that the action in the main clause happens <em>right after</em> that in the
relative clause.
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha go@KJ{{meal}}wo @KJ{{eat}}beru<strong>toki</strong> @KJ{{hand}}wo @KJ{{wash}}u.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I will wash my hands right before I eat my meal.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{private}}ha go@KJ{{meal}}wo @KJ{{eat}}beta<strong>toki</strong> @KJ{{hand}}wo @KJ{{wash}}u.}}      
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I will wash my hands right after I eat my meal.      
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{hiroshiha @KJ{{test^verification}}no<strong>toki</strong> kaze wo hikimashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Hiroshi caught a cold at exam time.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KT{{teri-}}ha @KT{{ju-su}}ga @KJ{{relax}}i<strong>toki</strong>ni takusan @KJ{{buy}}tte oita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Terry bought a lot of juice when it was cheap.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{country}}he @KJ{{homecoming}}ru <strong>toki</strong>, kabann wo @KJ{{buy}}imashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I bought a bag when I was going back to my country (and I bought it before I finished my journey).
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{country}}he @KJ{{homecoming}}tta <strong>toki</strong>, kabann wo @KJ{{buy}}imashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I bought a bag when I went back to my country (after my trip had been completed and I had already arrived in my country).
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>

<h2> Notes </h2>

<p>
<strong>@HI{{toki}}</strong> can be followed by an optional @HI{{ni}}, in which the time at which the relative clause
happened comes under particular focus.
</p>

<p>
A <strong>@HI{{toki}}</strong> clause never indicates a condiftion.
</p>

